Rebasing on FY25 results, which was above cons and basically in line with MSe. On EPS, we lift FY26- 27e \(2 - 3\%\) , predominately on the back of better margins and cost control (on call MMS noted c.57% cost to income ratio was achievable in FY26e, after \(58.7\%\) in FY25).

Our top line is little changed - balancing strong novated momentum (e.g. 2H25 c. \(+5\%\) pcp, despite cycling tougher comps with contract loss) with still relatively messy trajectories given contract losses that make underlying compares difficult (though a clear datapoint is that MMS grew revenues, despite these losses). We see scope for outperformance but keep some conservatism.
We also note that MMS is entering a period of lower contract renewal risk - c.10% of salary packages over next 18mths (after a relatively elevated period last few years).
We roll forward valuation to FY26e (on FY25A) and raise PT to A\(21.50.

- EPS growth is muddied by SA contract loss in FY25 (though well known) and incremental macro uncertainty.- However, we believe the company has levers to mitigate the loss - this was on display at 1H25 and 2H25, where MMS managed to grow GRS revenues, despite contract loss, with strong exit momentum.- We also find current multiples undemanding for a business that can generate high-single-digit EPS growth in outer years.- The stock is priced for cyclicality - despite (public) novated being historically resilient and less volatile as a category of auto demand.- It also offers \(6\% +\) dividend yield.

Greater focus brings contract wins, with further positive surprise from strategic review: Our bull case essentially has MMS more than making up for the earnings headwind from the contract loss. 1) Simply Stronger surprises positively on returns; 2) sharper focus leads to new contract wins (even if smaller); and 3) strong EV tailwinds continue in the medium term.

Public and not for profit exposure holds up earnings + EV tailwinds: Some headwinds to earnings are felt in the near term associated with potential macro headwinds and in FY25 specifically, loss of a large contract. However, we think the underlying demand trajectory remains resilient over FY25- 27e with EV tailwinds (penetration and new customer wins), new growth initiatives (top line and efficiency) and supported by low- single- digit customer employee growth. This was already on display in FY25.

Adverse impacts from regulation and macro conditions: Commission structures come under further review while the macro environment remains poor for new vehicle sales, depressing margins. Plan Partners growth also slows and is a marginal contributor to performance overall. Operating headwinds from moving to a diversified funding structure, affecting revenue and margins, and sorting out teething issues takes longer than expected.
